MAMBA FINE TUNING¶

Authors

  • Andrea Bonomi (a.bonomi021@studenti.unibs.it)
  • Giorgio Bucella (g.bucella002@studenti.unibs.it)
  • Riccardo Rossi-Erba (r.rossierba@studenti.unibs.it)

Introduction¶

  • The project began with an in-depth study of the Mamba architecture, a language model based on State Space Models (SSMs) rather than transformers.

    • While transformers remain the dominant paradigm, Mamba demonstrates efficiency and scalability through alternative design principles.
    • Commercial applications, such as Mistral’s Codestral, highlight Mamba’s practical relevance for specialized tasks like code generation.

  • After reviewing Mamba 2, the most efficient implementation of this architecture, the research focused on evaluating performance in a constrained environment (Google Colab), starting with the smallest model versions.

    • Implemented and assessed different fine-tuning techniques across various scales.
    • Comparisons were made against results reported in the original reference paper.

  • Environment setup included:

    • Tokenizer configuration.
    • Evaluation metrics via LM-eval to ensure reproducibility and benchmark consistency.
    • Dedicated functions for fine-tuning procedures to enhance clarity and repeatability.

  • Experiments focused on two datasets:

    • PiQA
    • ARC-e

  • Fine-tuning strategies employed:

    • Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)
    • Direct Preference Optimization (DPO)
    • LoRA parameter-efficient fine-tuning

  • All experiments were conducted using the Hugging Face platform, providing tools for:

    • Model management
    • Dataset handling
    • Efficient training workflows

  • The final stage will compare the results of fine-tuned models with larger baseline models on the same datasets, highlighting performance gains and efficiency trade-offs.

Plotting and Printing fine tuning log¶

  • These functions provide tools to retrieve, clean, and visualize training data from Weights & Biases (W&B) runs a posteriori, once the run is finished.

    • print_run_duration reports the total runtime of an experiment.
    • get_sft_train_df and get_dpo_train_df extract and organize training/evaluation histories for supervised fine-tuning (SFT) and direct preference optimization (DPO).
    • plot_sft_results and plot_dpo_results generate plots of loss curves (and accuracy for DPO), offering a quick view of training dynamics.
    • print_sft_table and print_dpo_table display aligned training and evaluation metrics in markdown tables alongside runtime. Altogether, they simplify performance tracking and comparison across fine-tuning runs.

def print_run_duration(wandb_run_id):
    api = wandb.Api()
    run = api.run(f'{wandb_user}/{wandb_project}/{wandb_run_id}')
    runtime_seconds = run.summary.get("_runtime", None)

    print(f'Run duration: {str(timedelta(seconds=runtime_seconds))}')
In [ ]:
def get_sft_train_df(wandb_run_id):
  wandb_run_name = f'r-rossierba-universit-degli-studi-di-brescia/mamba2/{wandb_run_id}'
  api = wandb.Api()
  run = api.run(wandb_run_name)
  history = run.history()

  # clean the dataframes
  eval_loss_history = history[history['eval/loss'].notna()]
  eval_loss_history = eval_loss_history.drop(columns=[col for col in eval_loss_history.columns if col not in ['eval/loss', 'train/global_step', 'train/epoch']])

  train_loss_history = history[history['train/loss'].notna()]
  train_loss_history = train_loss_history.drop(columns=[col for col in train_loss_history.columns if col not in ['train/loss', 'train/global_step']])

  return eval_loss_history, train_loss_history

def plot_sft_results(wandb_run_id):
  eval_loss_history, train_loss_history = get_sft_train_df(wandb_run_id)

  fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6), sharex=True)

  axes[0].plot(eval_loss_history['train/global_step'], eval_loss_history['eval/loss'], label='Eval Loss', color='orange')
  axes[0].set_title('Eval Loss')
  axes[0].legend()

  axes[1].plot(train_loss_history['train/global_step'], train_loss_history['train/loss'], label='Train Loss', color='red')
  axes[1].set_title('Train Loss')
  axes[1].legend()

  for ax in axes.flat:
      ax.set_xlabel('Global Step')
      ax.grid(True)

  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

def print_sft_table(wandb_run_id):
  print(f'Run id: {wandb_run_id}\n')
  eval_loss_history, train_loss_history = get_sft_train_df(wandb_run_id)
  train_loss_history = train_loss_history[train_loss_history['train/global_step'].isin(eval_loss_history['train/global_step'])]
  merged_df = pd.merge(train_loss_history, eval_loss_history, on='train/global_step')
  merged_df = merged_df[['train/epoch','train/global_step', 'train/loss', 'eval/loss']]
  merged_df.columns = ['Epoch', 'Step', 'Train Loss', 'Eval Loss']
  merged_df = merged_df.round(4)
  print_run_duration(wandb_run_id)
  print(merged_df.to_markdown(index=False))

def get_dpo_train_df(wandb_run_id):
  wandb_run_name = f'r-rossierba-universit-degli-studi-di-brescia/mamba2/{wandb_run_id}'
  api = wandb.Api()
  run = api.run(wandb_run_name)
  history = run.history()

  # clean the dataframes
  eval_loss_history = history[history['eval/loss'].notna()]
  eval_loss_history = eval_loss_history.drop(columns=[col for col in eval_loss_history.columns if col not in ['eval/loss', 'train/global_step', 'train/epoch', 'eval/rewards/accuracies']])

  train_loss_history = history[history['train/loss'].notna()]
  train_loss_history = train_loss_history.drop(columns=[col for col in train_loss_history.columns if col not in ['train/loss', 'train/global_step']])

  return eval_loss_history, train_loss_history

def plot_dpo_results(wandb_run_id):
  eval_loss_history, train_loss_history = get_dpo_train_df(wandb_run_id)

  fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 6), sharex=True)

  axes[0].plot(eval_loss_history['train/global_step'], eval_loss_history['eval/loss'], label='Eval Loss', color='orange')
  axes[0].set_title('Eval Loss')
  axes[0].legend()

  axes[1].plot(train_loss_history['train/global_step'], train_loss_history['train/loss'], label='Train Loss', color='red')
  axes[1].set_title('Train Loss')
  axes[1].legend()

  axes[2].plot(eval_loss_history['train/global_step'], eval_loss_history['eval/rewards/accuracies'], label='Accuracy', color='green')
  axes[2].set_title('Accuracy')
  axes[2].legend()

  for ax in axes.flat:
      ax.set_xlabel('Global Step')
      ax.grid(True)

  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

def eval_model(model, tokenizer, tasks):
  results = evaluator.simple_evaluate(
      model=HFLM(pretrained=model, tokenizer=tokenizer),

  )

Introduction to lm-eval Framework

  • Open-source framework for evaluating language models (LMs)
  • Provides a unified codebase, run new methods alongside standardized baselines
  • Supports a wide range of tasks (e.g., QA, reasoning, text generation)
  • Ensures consistency, reproducibility, and comparability across experiments
  • Built around three core components:
    • Tasks, define what to evaluate
    • Requests, define how to query the LM
    • Language Model APIs, connect different models with a unified interface

Tasks

  • Modular, standardized Task class implementations
  • Collected in a shared library, reusability across projects
  • Tasks include:
    • Multiple-choice QA (accuracy-based)
    • Perplexity measurement (fluency/likelihood)
    • Text generation (open-ended responses)
  • Enables fair comparisons between models on identical setups

Language Models & Requests

  • LMs are abstracted as systems processing Requests
  • Uniform interface supports multiple request types
  • Three primary request types:
    1. Conditional log-likelihoods, probability of candidate answers (multiple-choice)
    2. Perplexity, average likelihood across dataset, fluency & fit
    3. Text generation, open-ended model completions
  • Captures both generative and probabilistic capabilities of Language Models

Best Practices & Methodological Rigor

  • Emphasizes reproducibility and methodological robustness
  • Avoids model-specific hacks (e.g., prompt overfitting)
  • Promotes qualitative analysis of evaluation outcomes (interpretability)
  • Reports standard error (SE) for metrics:
    • Bootstrapping
    • Or sample variance scaling ($\sigma/\sqrt{n}$)
  • Easy extension for more statistical measurements
  • Supports transparent reporting and consistent workflows

Formalizing Measurements: Multiple-Choice QA

Ranking-Based Multiple-Choice QA

  • Focuses on conditional log-likelihood evaluation
  • Setup:
    • Auto-regressive LM with vocabulary $V$
    • Input tokens $x_0, …, x_{n-1}$, where the model predicts next token distribution
  • Output:
    • Logits: raw scores of shape $(n, |V|)$
    • Converted to log probabilities via log-softmax
  • Each token position provides $P(x_i \mid x_{<i})$

Computing Log-Likelihood of Candidate Answer

To evaluate candidate $y = (y_0, …, y_{m-1})$ given input $x$:

  1. Concatenate $x$ with $y$ (excluding last token)
  2. Run sequence through LM, get logits of shape $(n+m-1, |V|)$
  3. Apply log-softmax, convert logits into log probabilities
  4. Compute conditional log-likelihood:

$$\log P(y \mid x) = \sum_{i=0}^{m-1} \log p(y_i \mid x, y_{<i})$$

  • For $k$ candidates $a_1, …, a_k$:
    • Select $\arg\max_j \log P(a_j \mid x)$
    • Requires up to k LM calls

Challenges in Multiple-Choice QA

  • Bias toward shorter answers:
    • Log-likelihood sums, shorter sequences naturally score higher
  • Mitigation strategies:
    • Token-length normalization, average per-token score
    • Byte-length normalization (acc_norm), tokenizer-independent, fairer across models

Tokenizer Alignment Issues & Solutions

  • Problem: Input $x$ and candidate $y$ may tokenize inconsistently
  • Misalignment can distort conditional log-likelihood computation
  • Causes:
    • Tokenizer merges whitespace/punctuation differently
    • Training-time vs evaluation-time tokenization mismatch
  • Solutions:
    • Careful prompt design to minimize artifacts
    • Token healing → adjust boundaries between input & target
    • lm-eval heuristic:
      • Shift trailing whitespace into $y$ (target)
      • Exclude whitespace from $x$ (input)
      • Ensures cross-model consistency

Models¶

Architecture¶

Sequence Models

  • Designed to process inputs of arbitrary length across many domains
  • Modern sequence modeling is dominated by the Transformer architecture
    • Attention mechanism enables dense information routing within a fixed context window
    • Excels at modeling complex dependencies in sequential data

Limitations of Transformers

  • Fixed context window → cannot capture long-range dependencies efficiently
  • Extending context → significant computational & memory cost
  • Computational complexity:
    • Transformers: quadratic $O(L^2)$
    • Inefficient for very long sequences

Structured State Space Models (SSMs)

  • Emerging alternative to Transformers
  • Combine principles of:
    • State space models (control theory)
    • RNNs
    • CNNs
  • Two implementation styles:
    • Recurrent form → sequential updates
    • Convolutional form → parallelizable
  • Achieve linear or near-linear scaling with sequence length

Efficiency vs Performance

  • SSMs:
    • Linear complexity $O(L)$ in both compute & memory
    • Advantage: highly efficient on long sequences
  • Trade-off:
    • Standard SSMs often underperform Transformers in predictive accuracy
  • Recent progress:
    • Selective SSMs (e.g., Mamba)
    • Aim to preserve efficiency of SSMs
    • While approaching Transformer-level performance

Structured State Space Sequence Models (S4)

  • Structured State Space Models (SSMs / S4), modern sequence models combining:
    • Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs)
    • Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)
    • Classical state space models
  • Parameterized by four matrices $(\Delta, A, B, C)$
    • Define a sequence-to-sequence transformation
    • Applied in two stages:
      1. Discretization
      2. Token-wise linear RNN processing
  • Typically embedded inside larger architectures (e.g., deep networks)
  • Analogy: linear RNNs, combine previous hidden state with current token embedding
  • Tokens processed sequentially via $(\Delta, A, B, C)$ transformations

Stage 1 – Discretization

  • Converts continuous-time dynamics into discrete form
  • Starting point: differential equation
    $$\dot{h} = A h + B x$$
  • Discretization step with parameter $\Delta$ (learned during training):
    $$\overline{A} = \exp(\Delta A), \quad \overline{B} = (\Delta A)^{-1} (\exp(\Delta A) - I) \cdot \Delta B$$
  • $\Delta$ = step size
    • Too small, negligible updates
    • Too large, unstable dynamics

Stage 2 – Computation

  • Discrete hidden state updated iteratively:
    $$h_t = \overline{A} h_{t-1} + \overline{B} x_t$$
  • Output obtained via matrix $C$:
    $$y_t = C h_t$$
  • Optional direct input-to-output connection via matrix $D$:

Full Sequence Transformation

  • Applying matrices repeatedly enables efficient sequence modeling
  • Full token representation after $t$ steps:
    $$y_t = C \overline{A^t} \overline{B} x_0 + C \overline{A^{t-1}} \overline{B} x_1 + \dots + C \overline{B} x_t$$
  • Equivalent to a convolution with precomputed kernel $K$:
    $$K = (C \overline{B}, C \overline{A} \overline{B}, \dots, C \overline{A}^{L-1} \overline{B})$$
  • Enables efficient GPU-based convolution, scalable for very long sequences

Efficiency Properties

  • Scaling:
    • Linear in sequence length ($O(L)$)
    • Transformers scale quadratically ($O(L^2)$) due to self-attention
  • Adding one token = one additional computation
  • Training: parallelizable like linear RNNs
  • Kernel precomputation = highly efficient for long sequences

Limitations

  • Matrices $(A, B, C)$ are fixed across tokens
    • No input-dependent adaptation
    • Limits ability to focus selectively on different parts of sequence
  • Unlike LSTMs/GRUs, no gating mechanisms or hidden-state-dependent updates
  • May underperform on tasks requiring:
    • Selective attention
    • Highly context-dependent reasoning

Matrix Dimensions

  • S4 matrices have static dimensions:
    • $A, B, C$ depend only on model hyperparameters $(N, D)$
    • Independent of input sequence length
  • Ensures consistency across all tokens

Selective State Space Models (Mamba)

Motivation

  • Core challenge: compressing information into the model’s state
  • Transformers:
    • Self-attention provides powerful, context-dependent representations
    • But computationally expensive ($O(L^2)$)
  • Standard SSMs:
    • Highly efficient ($O(L)$)
    • But generally underperform attention-based models
  • Tradeoff: Efficiency vs Effectiveness
  • Limitation:
    • Traditional linear time-invariant (LTI) SSMs are non-selective
    • Apply identical transformations to all inputs
    • Lack expressivity and adaptability

Selection Mechanism in Mamba

  • Selective SSMs (e.g., Mamba) introduce input-dependent dynamics
  • For each token:
    • Matrices $\Delta$, $B$, $C$ are computed dynamically via linear projections

$$\Delta, B, C = f(s), \quad s = W x_{t}$$

  • Effect:
    • Model modulates tradeoff between current input vs existing state
    • Enables input-dependent focus (analogous to attention)

Parameter Roles

  • $\Delta$
    • Controls tradeoff between input and state
    • Large $\Delta$ → prioritize input
    • Small $\Delta$ → prioritize state
    • Analogous to gating mechanisms in RNNs
  • $A$
    • Core transition matrix
    • Its effect modulated by $\Delta$ during discretization → makes $A$ selective
  • $B$ and $C$
    • Regulate input-to-state and state-to-output transformations
    • Allow dynamic adaptation depending on both input and hidden state

Key Consequences

  • Input-dependent matrices → no precomputation of convolution kernel $\overline{K}$ possible
    • Each token requires recomputing $(\Delta, B, C)$
  • Despite this, computation remains linear in sequence length
  • Mamba combines:
    • SSM efficiency (linear scaling)
    • Attention-like selectivity (input-dependent focus)

Efficiency and Computation in Selective SSMs

Standard SSM Efficiency

  • Linear Time-Invariant (LTI) systems, fixed transformation matrices across inputs
  • Tradeoff:
    • Larger hidden states, more representational power
    • But also higher memory + computation cost
  • Two modes in S4:
    • Recurrent mode
      • Processes tokens sequentially
      • Complexity: $O(BLDN)$
      • May be preferable for long sequences with small hidden states
    • Convolutional mode
      • Derived from recurrent formulation
      • Allows precomputation
      • Complexity: $O(BLD \log L)$
      • Reduces cost by factor of $N$

Selective SSMs (Mamba)

  • Overcome fixed-matrix limitation of LTI systems
  • Compute $(\Delta, A, B, C)$ dynamically per input
  • Tradeoff:
    • Gains selectivity + performance
    • Loses ability to use convolutional mode during training
    • Computational cost increases

GPU Optimization Strategy

  • Mamba leverages modern GPU memory hierarchy:

    • Hidden state ($N$) stored in fast on-chip memory (SRAM)
    • Dynamic matrices $(\Delta, A, B, C)$ in global memory (HBM)
    • Computation (discretization + updates) happens in SRAM
    • Outputs ($B \times L \times D$) written back to global memory

  • Goal: maximize bandwidth and minimize latency

  • Uses parallel associative scan:

    • Efficiently computes inherently sequential dependencies
    • Stores intermediate results to accelerate updates
    • Preserves benefits of input-dependent selectivity

Memory Efficiency in GPUs

  • Problem: Many GPU ops limited by memory bandwidth, not compute

  • Standard parallel scan workflow:

    • Store $\overline{A}$ and $\overline{B}$ in HBM
    • Perform scan in SRAM
    • Intermediate results $(B, L, D, N)$ written back to HBM
      -, Requires $O(BLDN)$ memory ops, major bottleneck

  • Mamba solution: Fused GPU kernel

    • Combines discretization + scan + multiplication by $C$
    • Keeps operations in SRAM
    • Reduces I/O by factor of $N$
    • Improves throughput significantly

Backpropagation and Training

  • Hidden state not stored in fused computation
  • Gradients require access to hidden states, recomputation needed
  • Strategy: recompute on the fly
    • Avoids storing $O(BLDN)$ states
    • Computational cost: $O(BLD + DN)$
      • $BLD$: sequence processing
      • $DN$: matrix transformations
  • More memory-efficient and faster than HBM reads
  • Enables scalable training + inference for long sequences

SSMs Architecture

Selective SSMs as Building Blocks

  • Serve as core modules for larger neural architectures
  • Can be integrated into complex models (e.g., Mamba)
  • Retain efficiency advantages while improving representational flexibility

Mamba Layer

  • Extends S4 architecture by relaxing input-independence constraint
  • Brings S4 closer to LSTM-style adaptability while keeping:
    • Single-pass computation across the sequence
    • Parallelizable training (Transformer-like)
  • Enables input-dependent state transitions while preserving structured SSM computations
  • Only selected matrices are modified per input (via selective mechanisms)

Components of a Mamba Block

  1. Linear layer
    • Expands token embedding dimensionality (e.g., 64 → 128 in original implementation)
    • Provides additional representational capacity
  2. Canonical convolutional layer
    • Convolution over previous layer’s output
    • Followed by SELU activation
  3. Selective SSM module
    • Processes convolutional output
    • Incorporates prior token information via selective mechanism
  4. Input–SSM interaction
    • Compute: $\text{SELU}(\text{linear(input)})$
    • Multiply elementwise with SSM output
    • → Measures similarity between contextual representation and current token embedding
  5. Output linear layer
    • Projects back to target embedding dimension

Stacking Mamba Layers

  • Multiple Mamba layers = richer sequential modeling
  • Each layer integrates:
    • Selective memory (SSM context)
    • Input-dependent transitions
  • Allows capturing long-range dependencies without excessive depth

Implementation¶

  • We used three primary variants of the Mamba model: Mamba 130M, Mamba 370M, and Mamba 790M.

  • Additionally, we tested the Mamba 1.4B model as an approximate upper bound, given the limits of our development environment.

  • All experiments were conducted on Google Colab, and the choice of models was constrained by its available computational resources.

  • All models were pretrained and loaded using the Hugging Face transformers library through the AutoModelForCausalLM interface.

  • The reasons for this choice were the stability of Hugging Face’s framework and the convenience of accessing pretrained models.

  • The naming convention for base models (downloaded from Hugging Face Hub before any modifications) was:

    model_{number of parameters}

  • The naming convention for fine-tuned models was:

    model_{number of parameters}_{dataset}_{training technique}_{weight precision}

  • The default precision was torch.float32, which matches the standard precision used by the Mamba authors and serves as a baseline for comparisons.

  • Other precision settings were also explored to analyze model behavior under different numerical representations.

  • Fine-tuned models were stored in Google Drive, with folder structures reflecting the same naming convention:

    path = 'content/drive/MyDrive/mamba2/'
directory = '{path}/{dataset_name}/.../{model_name}'

          (act): SiLU()
          (in_proj): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=4096, bias=False)
          (x_proj): Linear(in_features=2048, out_features=96, bias=False)
          (dt_proj): Linear(in_features=64, out_features=2048, bias=True)
          (out_proj): Linear(in_features=2048, out_features=1024, bias=False)
        )
      )
    )
    (norm_f): MambaRMSNorm(1024, eps=1e-05)
  )
  (lm_head): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=50280, bias=False)
)

Datasets¶

  • Two datasets were used:
    • PIQA is a question answering dataset designed to evaluate reasoning based on physical common sense. It is usually evaluated using the log-likelihood-based multiple choice method.
    • ARC is a complex question answering dataset, divided into two subsets: Easy and Challenge. The questions come from standardized natural science tests. lm-eval uses a log-likelihood-based cloze evaluation.

  • As regards implementation, the convention for naming datasets is: dataset_{dataset name}.

  • We then defined functions to convert the original dataset into a dataset suitable for training.

  • The functions preprocess_sft and preprocess_dpo are functions that transform the dataset for the SFT technique and the DPO technique, respectively.

  • The SFT technique has several possible accepted formats, which is why the functions preprocess_sft_text and preprocess_sft_completion have been defined.

    • Depending on the technique you want to use, the preprocess_sft function must refer to one of the two functions just mentioned.
    • These two techniques will be analyzed later.

  • The evaluation for both datasets reports both acc and acc_norm on the possible answers.

PIQA¶

  • PIQA is a dataset designed to evaluate reasoning about physical commonsense through natural language.

  • It is formulated as a multiple-choice QA with two possible solutions (sol1, sol2), only one of which is correct.

  • Composition:

    • 16.113 examples for training,
    • 1.838 for validation,

An example of a PIQA item is as follows.

{
  “goal”: “How do I prepare a guinea pig cage for its new occupants?”,
  “sol1”: “Provide the guinea pig with a cage full of a few inches of bedding made of ripped paper strips, you will also need to supply it with a water bottle and a food dish.”,
  “sol2”: “Provide the guinea pig with a cage full of a few inches of bedding made of ripped jeans material, you will also need to supply it with a water bottle and a food dish.”,
  “label”: 0,
}

where,

  • goal: the question that requires common sense knowledge of physics to be solved correctly
  • sol1: the first solution
  • sol2: the second solution
  • label: the correct solution. 0 refers to sol1 and 1 refers to sol2

ARC-E¶

  • ARC is a dataset of multiple-choice questions taken from grade-school science tests.

  • The dataset is divided into two subsets:

    • Easy Set: relatively simple questions,
    • Challenge Set: questions that confused both retrieval-based and word co-occurrence-based systems

  • For our experiments, we only used the ARC-Easy subset.

  • Composition:

    • train, 2.251 questions
    • validation, 570 questions
    • test, 2.376 questions

An example of an ARC-Easy item is as follows.

{
    “answerKey”: “B”,
    “choices”: {
        “label”: [“A”, “B”, ‘C’, “D”],
        “text”: [“Shady areas increased.”, “Food sources increased.”, “Oxygen levels increased.”, “Available water increased.”]
    },
    “id”: “Mercury_SC_405487”,
    “question”: “One year, the oak trees in a park began producing more acorns than usual. The next year, the population of chipmunks in the park also increased. Which best explains why there were more chipmunks the next year?”
}

where,

  • id: question ID.
  • question: actual question.
  • choices: a dictionary representing the answers containing:
    • label: answer labels.
    • text: answer text.
  • answerKey: label of the correct answer.

# preprocess DPO for ARC-E dataset
def preprocess_dpo_v1(example):
  choices = example["choices"]['text']
  answer_key = example['answerKey']
  chosen = ""
  rejected = ""

  if answer_key == 'A' or answer_key == 1:
    chosen = choices[0]
    rejected = str(choices[1:])
  elif answer_key == 'B' or answer_key == 2:
    chosen = choices[1]
    rejected = str(choices[:1] + choices[2:])
  elif answer_key == 'C' or answer_key == 3:
    chosen = choices[2]
    rejected = str(choices[:2] + choices[3:])
  elif answer_key == 'D' or answer_key == 4:
    chosen = choices[3]
    rejected = str(choices[:3])

  example['prompt'] = example['question']
  example['chosen'] = chosen
  example['rejected'] = rejected
  return example

DPO V2

  • This is a technique based on how DPO works,

  • Each element in the dataset is splitted into three new elements.

Let's see an example.

'question': question,
'choices': [{'text': [option A, option B, option C, option D],
   'label': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']}],
'answerKey': ['B']

is splitted into

{'prompt':question, 'chosen': option B, 'rejected': option A}
{'prompt':question, 'chosen': option B, 'rejected': option C}
{'prompt':question, 'chosen': option B, 'rejected': option D}
  • This way we can have a dataset made by examples that are compatible with the classic DPO.
In [ ]:
from datasets import Dataset, DatasetDict

def preprocess_ds_dpo_v2(ds):

  new_ds = []

  new_i = ""
  id = 0

  for i in ds:
    choice = i['choices']['text']
    a_key = i['answerKey']

    if a_key == 'A' or a_key == 1:
      answer = choice[0]
      choice.pop(0)
      for c in choice:
        new_i = {'id': id, 'question': i['question'], 'choices': {'text': [answer, c], 'label': ['A', 'B']}, 'answerKey': 'A' }
        id += 1
        new_ds.append(new_i)

    if a_key == 'B' or a_key == 2:
      answer = choice[1]
      choice.pop(1)
      for c in choice:
        new_i = {'id': id, 'question': i['question'], 'choices': {'text': [answer, c], 'label': ['A', 'B']}, 'answerKey': 'A' }
        id += 1
        new_ds.append(new_i)

    if a_key == 'C' or a_key == 3:
      answer = choice[2]
      choice.pop(2)
      for c in choice:
        new_i = {'id': id, 'question': i['question'], 'choices': {'text': [answer, c], 'label': ['A', 'B']}, 'answerKey': 'A' }
        id += 1
        new_ds.append(new_i)

    if a_key == 'D' or a_key == 4:
      answer = choice[3]
      choice.pop(3)
      for c in choice:
        new_i = {'id': id, 'question': i['question'], 'choices': {'text': [answer, c], 'label': ['A', 'B']}, 'answerKey': 'A' }
        id += 1
        new_ds.append(new_i)

  return Dataset.from_list(new_ds)

Fine tuning¶

Experiments

  • We fine-tuned the selected pretrained Mamba models (130M, 370M, 790M, 1.4B parameters) using two training strategies:

    • Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)
    • Direct Preference Optimization (DPO)

  • The objective was to compare training stability and downstream performance across strategies and parameter scales.

  • Fine-tuning was implemented with the Hugging Face Transformers framework.

  • We used the default configuration of the Trainer class, which includes:

    • AdamW optimizer
    • Standard training utilities

  • Key hyperparameters systematically varied:

    • Learning rate: adaptation speed and convergence stability
    • Weight decay: regularization and overfitting control (especially for small models or limited data)
    • Learning rate scheduler: modulation of decay schedule and effect on training stability
    • Warmup ratio: proportion of steps with linear LR increase, improving early-phase stability

  • Hyperparameter selection was primarily based on manual tuning, aiming for:

    • Stable training dynamics
    • Good validation performance

  • Manual tuning was applied to:

    • Mamba-130M, Mamba-370M, and Mamba-790M on the PIQA dataset
    • Most ARC-E dataset runs

  • Resource constraints in Google Colab made large-scale hyperparameter sweeps infeasible.

  • The only exception was Mamba-130M with SFT on ARC-E, where a grid-search-style evaluation was performed for more systematic comparison.

  • This design balanced methodological rigor with practical feasibility, allowing exploration of model behavior under multiple optimization regimes within computational limits.

  • We evaluated both Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) and Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) because of their complementary strengths:

    • SFT → stable adaptation using cross-entropy loss on labeled data, but limited in aligning with nuanced human preferences
    • DPO → directly optimizes toward preference-based objectives, improving human alignment, but introduces greater training instability

  • Different numerical precisions were tested: torch.float16, torch.bfloat16, and torch.float32.

  • After several trials, we adopted torch.float32 as the default precision for Mamba-130M and Mamba-370M because:

    • It is the precision used by the Mamba authors in official evaluations
    • It consistently produced the most reliable results in our tests

  • Mixed precision was enabled by setting fp16=True.

  • Empirical observations:

    • Performance difference between full precision and mixed precision was negligible (< 0.01%)
    • Training time was reduced by roughly 50% with mixed precision
    • Training quality remained uncompromised

  • For Mamba-790M, we had to rely on torch.bfloat16 due to Colab environment constraints.

Supervised Fine-Tuning

  • Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) Trainer is the standard approach for training or fine-tuning large language models.

  • The SFT Trainer, from the Transformers Reinforcement Learning (TRL) library, is a high-level utility for adapting pretrained LMs to downstream tasks using supervised learning.

  • Unlike reinforcement learning methods (which rely on preference optimization or reward models), SFT directly minimizes cross-entropy loss between model outputs and reference responses.

  • The trainer is flexible with respect to input data formats:

    • Instruction–response pairs
    • Plain text corpora
    • Structured supervision signals
    • Any dataset that can be represented for causal language modeling

  • Internally, the SFT Trainer extends the Hugging Face Trainer API with:

    • Efficient data collation for generative models
    • Mixed-precision support
    • Easy integration with parameter-efficient fine-tuning (LoRA, adapters, etc.)

  • This makes it well-suited for rapid experimentation with Mamba, while maintaining reproducibility and compatibility with the Hugging Face ecosystem.

  • Examples of supported dataset formats:

# Standard language modeling
{"text": "The sky is blue."}

# Standard prompt-completion
{"prompt": "The sky is",
 "completion": " blue."}

  • In our experiments, we considered two styles of modeling:

    • Standard language modeling → each example became:

      {Question} {Right answer}

    • Prompt completion → each example became:

      {"prompt": "{Question}",
 "completion": "{Right answer}"}

Direct Preference Optimization

  • Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) Trainer is a reinforcement learning–inspired trainer for fine-tuning large language models.

  • Implemented in the Hugging Face TRL library, the DPO Trainer is based on the algorithm introduced by Rafailov et al. (2023).

  • It is designed as a simpler and more stable alternative to Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF).

  • Unlike RLHF (which requires a separate reward model and reinforcement learning loops), DPO directly optimizes a classification-style loss derived from preference data.

  • The DPO workflow consists of two main steps:

    1. Data collection → Build a dataset of prompt–response pairs, where each prompt has a positive (chosen) and a negative (rejected) response.
    2. Optimization → Apply the DPO loss to fine-tune the model, aligning it with human preferences in a classification-like fashion.

  • The required dataset format must include three fields:

    • prompt
    • chosen
    • rejected

  • In our case, each example was transformed as follows:

    {"prompt": "{Question}",
 "chosen": "{Right answer}",
 "rejected": "{Wrong answer}"}

  • This structure enables the trainer to compute the DPO loss using response pairs for each prompt.

  • Key advantages of DPO:

    • Computationally lightweight (no reward model or sampling loop needed)
    • Stable optimization compared to PPO-based RLHF
    • Reduced hyperparameter complexity
    • Demonstrated performance on par with, or better than, RLHF in tasks such as summarization, sentiment control, and single-turn dialogue.

class PersonalizedParams:
  def __init__(self,
               output_dir,
               num_train_epochs:int=3,
               eval_strategy='steps',
               eval_steps=200,
               save_strategy='steps',
               save_steps=5, # multiple of eval_steps
               save_total_limit=1,
               weight_decay=0.0,
               learning_rate=4e-5,
               batch_size=2,
               report_to='wandb',
               metric_for_best_model='eval_loss',
               load_best_model_at_end=True,
               gradient_accumulation_steps=1,
               warmup_ratio=0.05,
               lr_scheduler_type='linear',
               lr_scheduler_kwargs=None,
               save_safetensors=False
               ):
    self._output_dir = output_dir
    self._num_train_epochs = num_train_epochs
    self._batch_size = batch_size
    self._gradient_accumulation_steps = gradient_accumulation_steps

    # strategies
    self._eval_strategy = eval_strategy
    self._eval_steps = eval_steps
    self._save_strategy = save_strategy
    self._save_steps = save_steps
    self._save_total_limit = save_total_limit

    # optimizer
    self._weight_decay = weight_decay
    self._learning_rate = learning_rate
    self._warmup_ratio = warmup_ratio
    self._lr_scheduler_type = lr_scheduler_type
    self._lr_scheduler_kwargs = lr_scheduler_kwargs

    self._metric_for_best_model = metric_for_best_model
    self._load_best_model_at_end = load_best_model_at_end
    self._report_to = report_to
    self._save_safetensors=save_safetensors

    self._base_params = self._get_base_params()

  def _get_base_params(self):
    params = {}
    params['output_dir'] = self._output_dir
    params['num_train_epochs'] = self._num_train_epochs
    params['eval_strategy'] = self._eval_strategy
    if self._eval_strategy == 'steps':
      params['eval_steps'] = self._eval_steps
    params['save_strategy'] = self._save_strategy
    params['metric_for_best_model'] = self._metric_for_best_model
    params['load_best_model_at_end'] = self._load_best_model_at_end
    params['report_to'] = self._report_to
    params['gradient_accumulation_steps'] = self._gradient_accumulation_steps
    params['warmup_ratio']=self._warmup_ratio
    params['learning_rate']=self._learning_rate
    params['weight_decay']=self._weight_decay
    params['lr_scheduler_type']=self._lr_scheduler_type
    if self._lr_scheduler_kwargs is not None:
      params['lr_scheduler_kwargs']=self._lr_scheduler_kwargs

    params['save_safetensors']=self._save_safetensors

    if self._batch_size == 'auto':
      params['auto_find_batch_size'] = True
    else:
      params['per_device_train_batch_size'] = self._batch_size
      params['per_device_eval_batch_size'] = self._batch_size

    if self._save_strategy != 'no':
      if self._save_strategy == 'steps':
        params['save_steps'] = self._save_steps*self._eval_steps
      params['save_total_limit'] = self._save_total_limit

    return params

  def set_param(self, param, value):
    self._base_params[param] = value

  def get_arguments(self):
    return self._base_params

  def __repr__(self):
    lines = [f"PersonalizedParams("]
    for k, v in sorted(self._base_params.items()):
        lines.append(f"  {k}={v!r},")
    lines.append(")")
    return "\n".join(lines)

class PersonalizedTrainer:
  def __init__(self,
               model,
               strategy,
               params,
               peft_config=None,
               early_stopping_patience=None):
    self._model = model
    self._strategy = strategy
    self._params = params
    self._early_stopping_patience = early_stopping_patience
    self._peft_config = peft_config

  def _get_training_arguments(self):
    # training_arguments_params is a dictionary with specified parameters in PersonalizedParams
    training_arguments_params = self._params.get_arguments()

    if self._strategy == 'sft':
      training_arguments = SFTConfig(
          **training_arguments_params
      )
    elif self._strategy == 'dpo':
      training_arguments = DPOConfig(
          **training_arguments_params
      )
    else:
      raise ValueError('Strategy not supported')
    return training_arguments

  def get_trainer(self, dataset):
    training_arguments = self._get_training_arguments() # oggetto corretto in base alla strategia

    # dictionary to be passed at the Trainer with its params, it has to be completed with the right dataset based on the strategy
    trainer_arguments = {
        'model': self._model,
        'args': training_arguments,
        'processing_class':tokenizer
    }

    if self._early_stopping_patience is not None:
      print(f'Using early stopping patience: {self._early_stopping_patience}')
      trainer_arguments['callbacks'] = [EarlyStoppingCallback(early_stopping_patience=self._early_stopping_patience)]

    if self._peft_config is not None:
      print(f'Using peft config: {self._peft_config}')
      trainer_arguments['peft_config'] = self._peft_config

    # select the right strategy and preprocess the dataset for that strategy
    if self._strategy == 'sft':
      processed_dataset = dataset.map(
          preprocess_sft,
          remove_columns=dataset["train"].column_names,
          desc="Preparing dataset for SFT"
      )

      # defining dataset in the training arguments dictionary
      trainer_arguments['train_dataset'] = processed_dataset['train']
      trainer_arguments['eval_dataset'] = processed_dataset['validation']
      trainer = SFTTrainer(**trainer_arguments)
    elif self._strategy == 'dpo':
      processed_dataset = dataset.map(
          preprocess_dpo,
          remove_columns=dataset["train"].column_names,
          desc="Preparing dataset for DPO"
      )
      trainer_arguments['train_dataset'] = processed_dataset['train']
      trainer_arguments['eval_dataset'] = processed_dataset['validation']
      trainer = DPOTrainer(**trainer_arguments)
    else:
      raise ValueError('Strategy not supported')

    return trainer

  def init_wandb(self, name=""):
    run_name = self._params.get_arguments()['output_dir'].split('/')[-1]+name
    # this is the project we saved logs in
    wandb.init(entity="r-rossierba-universit-degli-studi-di-brescia", project="mamba2", name=run_name)

  def __repr__(self):
    model_name = getattr(self._model, 'name_or_path', None)
    if model_name is None:
        model_name = type(self._model).__name__
    return (
        f"PersonalizedTrainer(\n"
        f"  model={model_name},(dtype={self._model.dtype})\n"
        f"  strategy={self._strategy!r},\n"
        f"  early_stopping_patience={self._early_stopping_patience!r}\n"
        f"  peft_config={self._peft_config!r}\n"
        f")"
    )
In [ ]:
class MambaFineTuner:
  def __init__(self,
               dataset, # dataset not processed
               personalized_trainer : PersonalizedTrainer,
               checkpoint=None # checkpoint directory
               ):

    self._dataset = dataset
    self._trainer = personalized_trainer
    self._checkpoint = checkpoint

  def get_trainer(self):
    return self._trainer.get_trainer(dataset=self._dataset)

  def tune(self, save):
    trainer = self.get_trainer()

    if self._checkpoint is not None:
      self._trainer.init_wandb(self._checkpoint)
      trainer.train(resume_from_checkpoint=self._checkpoint)
    else:
      self._trainer.init_wandb()
      trainer.train()

    if save:
      trainer.save_model(save)

    wandb.finish()

    return trainer

Here follow the documentation of these classes.

Class PersonalizedParams

The PersonalizedParams class includes:

  • output_dir: directory where model and checkpoints are saved.
  • num_train_epochs: number of training epochs, default = 3.
  • eval_strategy: either 'steps' or 'epoch', default = 'steps'.
  • eval_steps: used if eval_strategy=='steps'; defines after how many steps the evaluation on the validation set is performed.
  • save_strategy: either 'steps' or 'epoch', default = 'steps'.
  • save_steps: used if save_strategy=='steps'; default = 2. It is a multiple of eval_steps and defines after how many evaluations a checkpoint is saved.
  • save_total_limit: if save_strategy!='no', default = 1.
  • Optimizer parameters (AdamW from Hugging Face Trainer):
    • weight_decay, default = 0.0.
    • learning_rate, default = 4e-5.
    • warmup_ratio, default = 0.0. Percentage of total steps during which the optimizer is in warmup (learning rate does not decrease).
    • lr_scheduler_type, name of the scheduler, default = 'linear'.
    • lr_scheduler_args, a dictionary with scheduler parameters, default = None.
  • batch_size: used for both training and evaluation, default = 8.
  • gradient_accumulation_steps: frequency of weight updates. The effective batch size is batch_size * gradient_accumulation_steps, which simulates a larger batch size (typically around 8).
  • report_to: logging backend, default = 'wandb'.
  • save_safetensors: whether to save the model in safetensors format, default = False. When saving to pytorch_model.bin no warnings are raised.
  • metric_for_best_model, default = 'loss'.
  • load_best_model_at_end, default = True.

Additional parameters can be added via the method set_param(param, value) where:

  • param: a string containing the parameter name.
  • value: the corresponding value (with correct type).

Class PersonalizedTrainer

The PersonalizedTrainer class includes:

  • model: the model to be trained.
  • strategy: either 'sft' or 'dpo', specified as a string.
  • params: a PersonalizedParams object with the chosen configuration.
  • early_stopping_patience: if set to a numeric value, activates early stopping with the specified patience.

This class creates the trainer with the chosen parameters:

  1. It builds the training arguments using the personalized configuration. The strategy determines whether an SFT or DPO configuration object is created.
  2. It instantiates the appropriate Trainer based on the strategy and the user preferences.

Class MambaFineTuner

The MambaFineTuner class includes:

  • dataset: the raw Hugging Face dataset (unprocessed).
  • personalized_trainer: a PersonalizedTrainer with the configured parameters.
  • checkpoint: default = None. If specified, it is the path to the directory containing the checkpoint information.

The tune method runs the training loop and saves the fine-tuned model. To avoid saving, one must explicitly call tune(save=False). By default, the model is saved.

PIQA - LoRA¶

  • We experimented with Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) to investigate whether this parameter-efficient fine-tuning technique could improve results.

  • Standard fine-tuning updates all weights of a pre-trained model.

    • Downside: the fine-tuned model contains as many parameters as the base model, leading to high computational and memory costs.

  • LoRA introduces a low-rank decomposition approach:

    • Instead of modifying the full weight matrix, LoRA trains two smaller update matrices (low-rank factors).
    • The original pre-trained weights remain frozen, while the smaller matrices are optimized.
    • At inference, the adapted weights are merged with the frozen weights to generate the final outputs.

  • Advantages of LoRA:

    • Parameter efficiency, drastically reduces trainable parameters, lowering training cost.
    • Modularity, adapters can be trained for different downstream tasks while keeping the same base model.
    • Compatibility, orthogonal to other parameter-efficient fine-tuning methods.
    • Performance, achieves accuracy comparable to full fine-tuning.
    • No inference latency, adapter weights can be merged into the base model, avoiding runtime overhead.
  • In practice:
    • LoRA can be applied selectively to chosen weight matrices within the network.
    • The number of trainable parameters depends on the rank $r$ of the update matrices relative to the original weight matrix.
    • While separate LoRA adapters are lightweight, maintaining them independently may introduce inference latency.
    • Solution: merge the LoRA weights with the base model. Since the two low-rank matrices ($A$ and $B$) recombine into a full matrix equivalent to the updated weights, the merged model becomes a standalone version without extra overhead.

PEFT Setup

  • We applied Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) to all selected Mamba models (130M, 370M, 790M, and 1.4B parameters).

  • Each model was fine-tuned on the PIQA dataset under both SFT and DPO settings.

  • To ensure comparability, we used a fixed LoRA configuration defined with Hugging Face’s peft library:

    • rank_dimension = 16

      • Controls the size of the low-rank decomposition.
      • Smaller rank, fewer trainable parameters, more efficiency, but reduced expressive capacity.

    • lora_alpha = 32

      • Scaling factor for the LoRA updates relative to frozen base weights.
      • Stabilizes training by preventing updates from being too weak or overly dominant.

    • lora_dropout = 0.1

      • Dropout probability (10%) applied to LoRA updates.
      • Helps regularize training and reduce overfitting.

    • target_modules = ["x_proj", "dt_proj", "in_proj", "embeddings"]

      • Modules suggested by Hugging Face documentation for Mamba models.
      • Excludes out_proj, which is not supported by LoRA.

    • task_type = "CAUSAL_LM"

      • Specifies causal language modeling as the downstream task.

  • This configuration (referred to as peft_config) strikes a balance between parameter efficiency and performance, while enabling systematic comparison across model scales and training strategies.

In [ ]:
from peft import LoraConfig

rank_dimension = 16
lora_alpha = 32
lora_dropout = 0.1

peft_config = LoraConfig(
    r=rank_dimension,
    lora_alpha=lora_alpha,
    lora_dropout=lora_dropout,
    bias="none",
    target_modules=["x_proj", "dt_proj", "in_proj", "embeddings"],
    task_type="CAUSAL_LM",
)

SFT with grid search¶

  • We performed a small grid search over key hyperparameters to optimize fine-tuning in the SFT setting.

  • The search consisted of two iterations of 18 training runs each, where we systematically varied learning rate, batch size, and weight decay.

  • This exploration was only feasible because of the relatively small size of the chosen datasets, which kept training time and memory usage manageable.

  • Running the same grid search on larger models was not possible within our Colab environment.

  • As expected, the differences across runs were marginal on such a small model, with performance variations of no more than 1%.

Results and final comments¶

  • Full results table can be found here

  • We focus here on a subset of results relevant to our initial experimental goals.

PIQA¶

mamba 130m bf16 SFT 64.47% 67.35%
mamba 130m bf16 DPO 64.47% 65.13%
mamba 130m fp32 SFT 64.47% 68.06%
mamba 130m fp32 DPO 64.47% 68.44%
mamba 370m fp32 SFT 69.47% 73.12%
mamba 370m fp32 DPO 69.47% 76.17%
mamba 790m bf16 SFT 72.14% 73,39%
mamba 790m bf16 DPO 72.14% 75,35%

  • The best model is the 370 million parameters Mamba

    • Fine-tuned with the DPO Trainer, got better results than the Mamba 2.8 billion parameters, the biggest Mamba model.
    • The Mamba 370M fine-tuned with DPO results are even comparable with Mamba2 2.7 billion parameters. Again, the biggest Mamba2 model.

  • The mamba 790M here was our upper bound due to the environment constraint. We had to rely on the torch.bfloat16 precision and we could not try much hyperparameters search.

LoRA Fine-Tuning

Model Dtype Trainer Accuracy (base) Accuracy (FT)
mamba 130m fp32 SFT 64.47% 65.20%
mamba 130m fp32 DPO 64.47% 65.56%
mamba 370m fp32 SFT 69.47% 70.95%
mamba 370m fp32 DPO 69.47% 70.73%
mamba 370m fp32 DPO 69.47% 71.23%
mamba 790m fp32 SFT 72.14% 73.39%
mamba 790m fp32 DPO 72.14% 75.57%
mamba 1.4b bf16 SFT 74.16% 74.59%

Observations

  • In our experiments, we explored two variants of SFT:

    1. Completion datasets: the loss is calculated only on the completion portion of each sequence.
    2. Text-based datasets: the cross-entropy loss is applied over the entire sequence.

  • We observed that the text-based approach consistently produced slightly better results, and therefore it was adopted for the subsequent experiments.

  • The most significant performance gains on PIQA were achieved with the DPO approach.

  • Unlike SFT, which trains only on correct answers, DPO presents both correct and incorrect options, allowing the model to learn by comparison.

  • This comparative learning mechanism proved particularly effective, although it often introduced overfitting: training loss decreased sharply while validation loss increased, typically near the end of each epoch.

  • Despite this drawback, DPO consistently outperformed SFT, achieving higher final accuracies—though at the cost of longer training times (≈3× slower than SFT).

Hyperparameter tuning played a critical role in maximizing performance:

  • Learning rate: strongly influenced adaptation speed and stability.
  • Weight decay: optimal values clustered around 0.01.
  • Warmup ratio: effective around 10% ± 5% of total steps.

The choice of evaluation metric depended on the training strategy:

  • For SFT, we relied on validation loss, reflecting generalization ability.
  • For DPO, we monitored rewards/accuracies (fraction of chosen rewards exceeding rejected ones), while also checking validation loss and reward margins to detect overfitting.

Several important insights emerged from our LoRA experiments:

  • Training efficiency:

    • LoRA required approximately the same time per epoch as full fine-tuning.
    • Memory consumption was substantially reduced, enabling training of larger models (e.g., Mamba 1.4B) within Colab.

  • Checkpoint size:

    • LoRA checkpoints were much smaller than full fine-tuned models, simplifying storage and model management.

  • Model size and effectiveness:

    • On smaller models (130M, 370M), LoRA produced limited improvements compared to full fine-tuning.
    • On larger models (790M, 1.4B), LoRA’s benefits became much more apparent.
    • For example, the Mamba 790M fine-tuned with LoRA and DPO outperformed the fully fine-tuned Mamba 790M.

Overall, results indicate that LoRA scales more effectively with larger architectures:

  • For small models, LoRA underperforms compared to full fine-tuning.
  • For large models, LoRA achieves results equal to or better than full fine-tuning.

ARC-E¶

Full Fine-Tuning

Model Trainer Accuracy (base) Accuracy (FT)
mamba 130m SFT 47.98% 51.77%
mamba 130m DPO 47.98% 51.98%
mamba 370m SFT 54.97% 60.48%
mamba 370m DPO 54.9% 55.60%
mamba 370m DPO v2 54.97% 60.86%
mamba 790m SFT 60.43% 64.18%
mamba 790m DPO v2 60.43% 67.34%

Observations

  • For the ARC-E dataset, we restricted all experiments to torch.float32 precision.

    • The dataset is relatively small, so memory constraints were not an issue.
    • This allowed us to avoid trade-offs associated with reduced precision.

  • As in the PIQA experiments, we adopted the text-based SFT approach:

    • Cross-entropy loss applied across the entire sequence.
    • Consistently yielded better results than completion-based training.

  • Baseline DPO results

    • The standard DPO setup generally performed worse—or at best comparable—to SFT.
    • This suggests that the benefits of preference-based training are less pronounced on ARC-E.

  • Refined DPO v2 results

    • Produced a noticeable improvement over baseline DPO.
    • Effectiveness varied by model size:
    • Smaller models (Mamba 130M, 370M):
      • SFT remained more effective and efficient.
      • Equal or superior performance compared to DPO v2.
      • Shorter training times.
    • Larger models (Mamba 790M):
      • DPO v2 outperformed SFT.
      • Gains came at the cost of substantially longer training times.

Summary:

  • For smaller architectures, SFT is generally the more practical choice (better or equal performance, faster training).
  • For larger architectures, DPO v2 becomes increasingly advantageous, delivering superior results despite higher computational costs.

Final Comments¶

  • This work demonstrates that fine-tuning can substantially reduce computational and memory requirements while still achieving competitive performance on benchmark datasets.

  • Key finding:

    • The Mamba 370M model (~1.5 GB) was able to match or surpass the performance of the much larger 2.8B model (~11 GB).
    • This highlights the potential of fine-tuned smaller models as practical alternatives to significantly larger architectures.

  • Consistency across experiments:

    • Fine-tuning often enabled a model to perform at the level of the next parameter tier:

    • Fine-tuned Mamba 130M ≈ baseline 370M

    • Fine-tuned Mamba 370M ≈ baseline 790M

    • Fine-tuned Mamba 790M ≈ baseline 1.4B / 2.8B

    • This demonstrates the effectiveness of fine-tuning as a strategy to enhance efficiency without adding parameters.

  • Main insight:

    • The choice of fine-tuning technique often matters more than raw model size.
    • Even within constrained environments like Google Colab, carefully chosen fine-tuning methods unlocked significant performance gains.
    • This enables the deployment of capable models on less powerful hardware, without compromising accuracy or efficiency.

Future work¶

A direction for future work is a deeper exploration of Mamba 2, the next-generation state space model architecture.

  • Key innovations in Mamba 2:

    • Leverages State Space Duality (SSD): the state transition matrix is reduced to a scalar-times-identity form.
      • Preserves the ability to model long-range dependencies.
      • Enables 2–8× faster computation compared to the original Mamba design.
    • Introduces parallel parameter computation, grouped projections, and efficient tensor parallelism, improving scalability in resource-constrained environments.

  • These improvements suggest that Mamba 2 could be a strong candidate for fine-tuning and deployment on limited hardware, while remaining competitive with Transformer-based approaches.

Another important direction is to extend fine-tuning beyond supervised and preference-based approaches, by exploring reinforcement learning-based methods, such as GRPO and PPO:

  • GRPO (Guided Reinforcement Policy Optimization):

    • Online learning algorithm that iteratively improves using data generated by the model itself.
    • Objective: maximize the advantage of generated completions while keeping the policy close to a reference, balancing exploration and stability.

  • PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization):

    • Policy-gradient method that improves learning stability.
    • Uses a clipped surrogate objective to limit policy changes per update.

Investigating integration of GRPO and PPO with Mamba and Mamba 2 could:

  • Provide insights into how state space architectures respond to reinforcement-driven optimization.
  • Assess whether efficiency advantages of Mamba architectures extend to more complex training paradigms.
